    <p>
        <activity xml:id="activity-T8Exploration1">
                    <p>
                        Consider <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x^2}.</m>
                    
                    Compute the following definite integrals.
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{0.1}^1 \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{0.01}^1 \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{0.001}^1 \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </activity>
         <activity>
             <task>
                <p>
                    What do you notice about <m>\displaystyle \int_{a}^1 \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m> as <m>a</m> approached 0 in <xref ref="activity-T8Exploration1"/>?
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    Why can't the lower bound be <m>0</m>?
                </p>
            </task>
        </activity>
        
        <activity xml:id="activity-T8Exploration2">
            
                    <p>
                        We still are considering <m>f(x)=\frac{1}{x^2}.</m>
                    
                    Compute the following definite integrals.
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^{10} \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^{100} \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                        <li><m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^{1000} \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
        <activity>   
            <p>
                    What do you notice about <m>\displaystyle \int_{1}^a \frac{1}{x^2} dx.</m> as <m>a</m> approached <m>\infty</m> in <xref ref="activity-T8Exploration2"/>?
            </p>
        </activity>
            
           
                
